TY  - JOUR
T1  - How can Cooperation be Fostered? The Cultural Effects of Individualism-Collectivism
AU  - Chen, Chao C.
AU  - Chen, Xiao-Ping
AU  - Meindl, James R.
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1998.533227
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1998.533227
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 285
EP  - 304
VL  - 23
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Studies of cooperation are abundant in the social sciences, but organizational researchers are calling for integrating the numerous conceptions of cooperation and meeting the new challenges of cultural differences. In this article we develop a culturally contingent model of cooperation. We differentiate various mechanisms from cooperative behaviors and theorize about how culture affects behavioral cooperation through mechanism selection or modification. Delineating cultural effects, we derive patterned differences in the instrumental and expressive motives of individualists and collectivists and propose six culturally contrasting cooperation mechanisms. Finally, we discuss directions for future research and consider implications for practice.
AB  - Studies of cooperation are abundant in the social sciences, but organizational researchers are calling for integrating the numerous conceptions of cooperation and meeting the new challenges of cultural differences. In this article we develop a culturally contingent model of cooperation. We differentiate various mechanisms from cooperative behaviors and theorize about how culture affects behavioral cooperation through mechanism selection or modification. Delineating cultural effects, we derive patterned differences in the instrumental and expressive motives of individualists and collectivists and propose six culturally contrasting cooperation mechanisms. Finally, we discuss directions for future research and consider implications for practice.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1998.533227
